<DOC><DOCNO> AP891220-0039 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-89 0344EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     12-20 0441</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,450</SECOND><HEAD>Eighteen State Legislatures Targeted by Democrats</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Statehouse races in 18 states will be targetednext year by Democrats who hope to control state legislatures whencongressional districts are redrawn for the 1990s.   Democrats will try to raise $3 million to help candidates forthe legislatures in those states next year, Tim Dickson, who headsthe party's Project 500 program, said Tuesday.   Democrats are particularly concerned with states likely to gainor lose congressional districts as a result of population shiftsthat will come to light in the 1990 census. They are also focusingon states where the majority's grip in the state legislature istenuous.   The targeted states are Arizona, California, Colorado,Connecticut, Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Michigan, NewJersey, New York, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Texas, Virginia,Washington and Wisconsin.   Democrats now control 36 state Houses and 32 state Senates,while Republicans control 12 Houses and 17 Senates. They sharepower in Indiana's House; Nebraska has a nonpartisan bicamerallegislature.</TEXT><HEAD>Sears, Government Settle Insulation Ads Complaint</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sears, Roebuck andamp; Co. has agreed to pay a$100,000 civil penalty to settle a dispute with the government overinsulation ads, the Federal Trade Commission said.   The FTC said Sears or its representatives had failed to includedetails on the insulation's heat resistance when it promoted thethickness and price of the product.   The ads ran within the last five years.   Chicago-based Sears has agreed to create an advertisementdesigned to educate consumers about home insulation, especially theimportance of having heat-resistance information when making apurchase, the FTC said Tuesday.   ``The violations were technical in nature and did not result inany consumer complaints,'' Sears spokesman Gordon Jones said.``There was no misrepresentation or deception involved.''   The settlement must be approved by a federal judge inWashington. The FTC said the consent decree does not constituteadmission of a law violation. The penalty is paid to thegovernment, not consumers.</TEXT><HEAD>Government Upgrades Beretta Investigation</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The National Highway Traffic SafetyAdministration says it's upgrading an investigation of a possiblesteering deficiency in the 1988 Chevrolet Beretta.   The agency also said Tuesday it was beginning probes of reportedexplosions in the heating systems of Coachmen Industriesrecreational vehicles and of cruise control failures in the FordTaurus and Mercury Sable.   The agency said it was stepping up its Beretta probe from apreliminary evaluation, which involves mostly paperwork, to anengineering analysis, in which the possibly defective parts areexamined.   Such investigations can lead to recalls or can be dismissed ifengineers decide there is no widespread safety problem.</TEXT></DOC>